<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-307-050  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 307 050.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computers in Healthcare  June 1989 v10 n6 p52(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Severity of illness measures: can they work for us? (patientclassification systems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Arbitman, Deborah B.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Healthcare managers are concerned with measuring the structure,process and outcome of healthcare to provide patients withhigh-quality, cost-effective healthcare.andP;  Patient classificationsystems are tools to provide insight into the evaluation of bothprocess and outcome.andP;  Inappropriate practice patterns must beidentified and corrected and severity-of-illness systems areuseful in this effort.andP;  Critics think, however, that severitysystems are of no more use than diagnosis-related groups (DRG) andthat these tools require detailed data collection that isexpensive and time consuming.andP;  Four systems, Disease Staging,Computerized Severity of Illness System, Medical Illness SeveritySystem and Patient Management Categories, are reviewed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Health CareQuality ControlMeasurement TechniquesPatientsClassification Systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Process. (chart)Outcome. (chart)DRG 295 - diabetes age 0-35. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>